<quantity box="[1071,1158,797,823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,863,1147]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">SHELL. Ovate-fusiform, with a cyrtoconoid spire. Primary spire callus thick, weakly microshagreened, covering all whorls, including most of protoconch rendering measurements inaccurate, and with weak spiral lirae (8–10 on penultimate whorl). Secondary callus medium thick, forming extensive pad on right side of spire. Plication plate with 2–4 (usually 3) ridges. Olivoid groove from shallow to rather deep, labral denticle weak, obtuse. Upper anterior band very weakly convex, nearly flat. Lower anterior band flat, smooth. Colour from uniformly white, to chestnut brown. In darker coloured specimens, primary spire callus and upper anterior band darker, olivoid band lighter than body whorl cloak, plication plate white.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1398,1188,1288]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
RADULA (n =2, not sequenced) (
<figureCitation box="[569,655,1188,1214]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="35.[189,232,1756,1782]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,829,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[189,1398,829,1711]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Fig. 13. Radulae of species of Amalda H. Adams &amp; A. Adams, 1853. A–C. A. montrouzieri (Souverbie, 1860). A–B. Île Ouen – Baie du Prony, LAGON, stn DW239, 22°24.3′ S, 166°57.8′ E, 42–43 m, SL 20.2 mm. C. Grand Récif Sud, LAGON, stn DW544, 22°50.8′ S, 166°48.5′ E, 25 m, SL 25.4 mm (shell on Fig. 12I). D–E. A. alabaster sp. nov. D. Holotype, MNHN IM-2007-43627, SL 26.7 mm (shell on Fig. 15A–B). E. MNHN IM-2007-43636, SL 17.6 mm. F. A. cf. alabaster, MNHN IM-2013-63897, SL 18.1 mm (shell on Fig. 15H–I). G. A. allaryi Bozzetti, 2007, MNHN IM-2013- 68272 (shell on Fig. 17A). H. A. coriolis Kilburn &amp; Bouchet, 1988, MNHN IM-2013-63899 (shell on Fig. 18H–I)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4010980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4010980/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
A–C). Very similar in these two. Central tooth tricuspid, with central cusp ¼ smaller than lateral ones. All cusps, as well as lateral flaps of central tooth, with irregular distinct serration.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1329,1429]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
LIVE SPECIMENS (
<figureCitation box="[381,464,1329,1355]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="36.[189,232,1926,1952]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,329,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[189,1398,329,1877]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Fig. 14. A–B. Live specimens of Amalda montrouzieri (Souverbie, 1860), Nouméa, 8 m. C–E. Shell and live specimen of A. herberti Cossignani, 2013, Nouméa, South Lagoon, about 250 m. Photos courtesy of David Massemin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4010982" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4010982/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
A–B). With truncated and notched posteriorly foot. Parapodia opaque, greyish, with scarce slightly darker speckles, can completely envelop shell. Propodium, anterior part of parapodia and siphon with more dense speckles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,303,1470,1496]" box="[189,303,1470,1496]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1470,1496]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1470,1496]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1517,1765]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
The species is quite variable in shell shape and particularly in colouration, with many specimens pure white or with lightly coloured secondary callus (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[810,932,1554,1581]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[189,232,1598,1624]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1534]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[189,1398,265,1534]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 12. Amalda montrouzieri (Souverbie, 1860), southern New Caledonia. A–C. Syntype MNHN IM- 2000-1475, SL 41.4 mm. D–E. MNHN IM-2013-80199, SL 18.7 mm (sequenced specimen). F. Secteur Île Ouen-Baie du Prony, LAGON, stn DW98, 22°35.7′ S, 166°31.8′ E, 15 m, SL 25.6 mm. G. Grand Récif Sud, LAGON, stn DW334, 22°38′ S, 166°53.6′ E, 47–48 m, SL 26.6 mm (illustrated by Kilburn &amp; Bouchet 1988: fig. 14). H. Secteur de Nouméa. LAGON, stn DW51, 22°14.7′ S, 166°11.1′ E, 10 m, SL 27.6 mm. I. Grand Récif Sud, LAGON, stn DW544, 22°50.8′ S, 166°48.5′ E, 25 m, SL 25.4 mm. J–K. A. cf. montrouzieri. Deep-water morph, SMIB2, stn DW23, 22°31′ S, 167°37′ E, 410–420 m, SL 30.2 mm (specimen illustrated by Kilburn &amp; Bouchet 1988: figs 5–6). All specimens except D–E not sequenced. Shells at the same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4010978" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4010978/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 12F, I</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[1006,1109,1555,1581]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">syntypes</typeStatus>
are the largest examined specimens. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kilburn R. N. &amp; Bouchet P." box="[329,714,1591,1617]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="277 - 300" refId="ref31223" refString="Kilburn R. N. &amp; Bouchet P. 1988. The genus Amalda in New Caledonia (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Olividae, Ancillinae). Bulletin du Museum national d'histoire naturelle, ser. 4, 10, section A 2: 277 - 300." type="journal article" year="1988">Kilburn &amp; Bouchet (1988: 281)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned the existence of “a puzzling morph which is uniformly different in shape (although there are indications of intergradation in this regard) and in its faint ancillid (=olivoid) groove” at larger depths (
<quantity box="[784,922,1664,1691]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.975" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="1.75" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="297.5" valueMax="420.0" valueMin="175.0">175–420 m</quantity>
) (
<figureCitation box="[949,1035,1665,1691]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[189,232,1598,1624]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1534]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[189,1398,265,1534]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 12. Amalda montrouzieri (Souverbie, 1860), southern New Caledonia. A–C. Syntype MNHN IM- 2000-1475, SL 41.4 mm. D–E. MNHN IM-2013-80199, SL 18.7 mm (sequenced specimen). F. Secteur Île Ouen-Baie du Prony, LAGON, stn DW98, 22°35.7′ S, 166°31.8′ E, 15 m, SL 25.6 mm. G. Grand Récif Sud, LAGON, stn DW334, 22°38′ S, 166°53.6′ E, 47–48 m, SL 26.6 mm (illustrated by Kilburn &amp; Bouchet 1988: fig. 14). H. Secteur de Nouméa. LAGON, stn DW51, 22°14.7′ S, 166°11.1′ E, 10 m, SL 27.6 mm. I. Grand Récif Sud, LAGON, stn DW544, 22°50.8′ S, 166°48.5′ E, 25 m, SL 25.4 mm. J–K. A. cf. montrouzieri. Deep-water morph, SMIB2, stn DW23, 22°31′ S, 167°37′ E, 410–420 m, SL 30.2 mm (specimen illustrated by Kilburn &amp; Bouchet 1988: figs 5–6). All specimens except D–E not sequenced. Shells at the same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4010978" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4010978/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
J–K). This morph differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Souverbie" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[189,370,1702,1728]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="montrouzieri">
<emphasis box="[189,370,1702,1728]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">A. montrouzieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kantor &amp; Castelin &amp; Fedosov &amp; Bouchet, 2020" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Castelin &amp; Fedosov &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2020" box="[425,561,1701,1727]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="alabaster" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[425,561,1701,1727]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">A.alabaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[567,656,1702,1728]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in its narrower shell with taller spire. It may represent a peculiar morph of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kantor &amp; Castelin &amp; Fedosov &amp; Bouchet, 2020" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Castelin &amp; Fedosov &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2020" box="[305,448,1738,1765]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="alabaster" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[305,448,1738,1765]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">A. alabaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[455,546,1739,1765]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
or a separate species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,342,1805,1831]" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1853,2027]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[307,497,1853,1880]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Souverbie" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[511,764,1853,1879]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="montrouzieri">
<emphasis box="[511,764,1853,1879]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Amalda montrouzieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is normally distributed at depths of 
<quantity box="[1220,1330,1854,1880]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="40.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="10.0">10–70 m</quantity>
, with specimens occasionally collected down to 
<quantity box="[707,789,1890,1917]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="130.0">130 m</quantity>
; a few empty shells were collected at even larger depths, down to 
<quantity box="[380,453,1927,1954]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="280.0">280 m</quantity>
(SMIB 3, stn DW20). 
<bibRefCitation author="Kilburn R. N. &amp; Bouchet P." box="[717,1026,1927,1953]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="277 - 300" refId="ref31223" refString="Kilburn R. N. &amp; Bouchet P. 1988. The genus Amalda in New Caledonia (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Olividae, Ancillinae). Bulletin du Museum national d'histoire naturelle, ser. 4, 10, section A 2: 277 - 300." type="journal article" year="1988">Kilburn &amp; Bouchet (1988)</bibRefCitation>
cited some extralimital records, mostly on the basis of published records, namely the 
<collectingRegion box="[818,1003,1964,1990]" country="New Caledonia" name="Province des Iles" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Loyalty Islands</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1059,1964,1990]" name="Fiji" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fiji</collectingCountry>
, the 
<collectingRegion box="[1115,1300,1964,1990]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ryukyu Islands</collectingRegion>
, and the 
<collectingCountry box="[189,325,2001,2027]" name="Philippines" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Philippines</collectingCountry>
. These records should be confirmed with molecular data.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
